--PROBLEM- TOP COMPETITORS
--LEARNED-
INNER JOIN with multiple tables.
Understanding table relationships before writing JOINs.
Using GROUP BY to group records by hacker.
Using COUNT(DISTINCT column) to avoid counting duplicate challenges.
Using HAVING to filter grouped results.
Comparing columns from different tables (Submissions.score = Difficulty.score).
Sorting results using multiple conditions in ORDER BY.
Understanding the difference between challenge creator (Challenges.hacker_id) and challenge solver (Submissions.hacker_id).
Following the correct join path based on table relationships instead of joining tables just because they have a column with the same name.

--SOLUTION- 
select h.hacker_id , h.name from hackers as h
inner join submissions as s
on h.hacker_id=s.hacker_id
/*join challenges as c
on h.hacker_id=c.hacker_id <- this is wrong becauase in challenges , the hacker_id represents who created the challenge , and in the submissions, it represents who solve the challenge , and we need that who solved the more than one  challenge , so if we join this , will give wrong name that who solved the challenge, no, it will give who creates the challenge*/
JOIN Challenges c
    ON s.challenge_id = c.challenge_id
join difficulty as d
on c.difficulty_level=d.difficulty_level
where s.score = d.score
group by h.hacker_id, h.name
having count(distinct s.challenge_id)>1
order by count(distinct s.challenge_id) desc  ,            
h.hacker_id asc;
